  "slug": "dream-bars-toffee-coconut",
  "title": "Dream bars",
  "subtitle": "Shortbread base with a toffee coconut and walnut topping",
  "excerpt": "A two-layer traybake: a buttery shortbread base pressed into the tin and par-baked, then covered with a sticky toffee topping made from eggs, golden syrup, and desiccated coconut before going back into the oven until set and caramelised. The bottom layer provides the crisp, buttery contrast to the chewy, sweet top. Cut into small bars once completely cool; they keep for several days in an airtight tin.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Two-layer traybake bars with a shortbread or pastry base and a sweetened coconut or nut topping are documented in North American and British home-baking literature from the early twentieth century. Fannie Farmer, The Boston Cooking-School Cook Book (first edition 1896, fully in the public domain and available at Project Gutenberg), describes similar layered bar formats. The golden syrup coconut topping style is found in British and Canadian domestic baking guides from the 1920s.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The two-step bake is what keeps the base crisp: ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "par-baking the shortbread layer",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "term": "Par-baking a traybake base",
                  "termId": "cmppnm7560000asv4uk9lusjp"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": " before adding the coconut topping prevents the base from going soggy. Let the base cool for 5 minutes before adding the topping so the egg mixture does not cook on contact.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
